1.2. Corticoides and inflammation: The powerful of glucocorticoides or cortisonic anti-inflammatoires
proprietes have been prominently displayed thanks to a rheumatologist, PH Hench, which had remarked
in the year 1938 of the favorable action of the gestations of the of the icterus on the polyarthritis
rhumatoide. Ten years later, he had the idea of to testing glucocorticoides provided by Kendall to treat
with success 21 patients having polyarthritis rhumatoild.
If starting assumption of Hench revel has errors: the remission of the polyarthritis rheumatoid is not due to
the natural secretion of glucocorticoides but has immunological factors, on the other hand the powerful
anti-inflammatory proprietes drugs of the corticoides are confirmed in numerous domaines of pathology.
These proprietes is exercised on all the phases of the inflammation reaction,which comprise of the more
initial stages.
After the works of Jeissian and Col. In the year 19633, which remarks the inhibitions of the cortisone ,of
the release of the enzymes lysosomials, then those of Gryglewski in 1975, which will demonstrate that the
cortisonics inhibit the synthesis of prostaglandin by blocking the release of their precursor ,the acid
arachidonic, from the membranary phospholipides, The comprehension of the effects of cortisonic on the
inflammation is l unfinished.. Recent work (1) shows that the cortisonics act on the inflammation by
inducing 13 synthesis of specific proteins, the lipocortines. It is mainly thanks to the proteins, veritable
"second messengers" of the cortisonic which exercise their inflammatory actions on the cellular
membranes.
